DC-1

Target IP: 192.168.170.193

Scanning



There are four main TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH, HTTP, RPC, and another RPC. I will start my enumeration with port 80 application!

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP


It looks like Drupal is used for the port 80 application. It is currently using the version 7, which is vulnerable to RCE. Before firing any exploits, I wish to enumerate further.


Using droopescan, I managed to find more information about the application such as the user login page. Default credentials did not work either when trying to login. After some manual enumeration, I did not find anything useful.

Exploitation


I used exploit/multi/http/drupal_drupageddon exploit to attack the target machine. This exploit relies on SQL injection to achieve a remote shell on the vulnerable machine, so no authentication is required.


Setting the values of the exploit.


And I have a foothold on the machine.

Privilege Escalation


Upgrading to an interactive Python shell.


It's nice that this box gives us hints throughout the way!


The first flag gives us the hint above.


This is the config file which contains the DB username and password!


Using the credentials dbuser:R0ck3t to gain access to MySQL.


I obtained the users table. The hash for Drupal X8gdX7OdYRiBnlHoj0ukhtZ7eO4EDrvMkhN21SWZocs.


Looks like we can use the /usr/bin/find binary to elevate to root.


And now I have a root shell by using the command ./find . -exec /bin/sh \; -quit.
